					<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content"><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Jean-Jacques_Rousseau_(painted_portrait).jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Jean-Jacques_Rousseau_%28painted_portrait%29.jpg/250px-Jean-Jacques_Rousseau_%28painted_portrait%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="250" height="348" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Jean-Jacques_Rousseau_%28painted_portrait%29.jpg/500px-Jean-Jacques_Rousseau_%28painted_portrait%29.jpg 1.5x" data-file-width="1448" data-file-height="2016" /></a><figcaption>Man is born free; and everywhere he is in chains.</figcaption></figure>
<p><b><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Jacques_Rousseau" class="extiw" title="w:Jean-Jacques Rousseau">Jean-Jacques Rousseau</a></b> (<a href="/wiki/June_28" title="June 28">June 28</a>, <a href="/wiki/1712" class="mw-disambig" title="1712">1712</a> – <a href="/wiki/July_2" title="July 2">July 2</a>, <a href="/wiki/1778" class="mw-disambig" title="1778">1778</a>) was a major French-speaking Genevan philosopher of the Enlightenment whose political ideas influenced the <a href="/wiki/French_Revolution" title="French Revolution">French Revolution</a>, the development of socialist theory, and the growth of nationalism.
</p>
<dl><dd>See also:
<dl><dd><i><b><a href="/wiki/Discourse_on_the_Arts_and_Sciences" title="Discourse on the Arts and Sciences">Discourse on the Arts and Sciences</a></b></i> (1750)</dd>
